$interpreted: Jihasaha: Prin... cess?
Tindoiimu: Why would you lie to me about your injuries!? If Tingko hadn't rushed in, you could have died!
Jihasaha: (Saved by the brat...)
Jihasaha: I... didn't want to... worry you...
Tindoiimu: So you think I'm not worried now!?
Jihasaha: I... I'm sorry...
Tindoiimu: You... agh, forget it! It's impossible to have a real conversation with you!

Tindoiimu: Tingko, stay and watch him. 
And Jihasaha... just stay put.
Jihasaha: Princess...
Jihasaha: You win... just don't touch me...
Tingko: Excuse me?

Jihasaha: Stop pretending. 
We've been at each other's throats... and I've lost. You've won.
Tingko: How could you even think about that right now? Just give me your hand. Or are you still not gonna' listen to me?
Tingko: Good~
Jihasaha: ......
Tingko: (He's been completely silent... He must feel so defeated. And I've never seen the princess so angry...)
Tingko: Jihasaha, can you tell me about how you and the princess met?
Jihasaha: ...?
Tingko: Just humor me. I want to get to know the princess a little more.
Jihasaha: It started when we were kids... I tried to pickpocket her.
Tingko: You tried to steal from the princess!?
Jihasaha: I didn't know who she was at the time. To me, she just looked like some rich, easy target.
Jihasaha: Stealing was my life. For survival, day to day. So that's all people were to me... money, targets... a way to survive.
Jihasaha: But I slipped up, and the princess was stronger than I expected.
Jihasaha: And then while protecting my buddy, something weird happened. Guards rushed in, and she held them off, letting me escape.
Tingko: That's because she appreciates loyalty.
Jihasaha: And then, I couldn't understand it... but when I found her later that night, she wasn't scared. She was even welcoming...
Jihasaha: We spent the whole night chatting under the moonlight about our hopes and dreams...
Jihasaha: And that's when I knew it... I had found the one I was looking for. The one who could change the future of the Insect Tribe.
Jihasaha: That night, I signed up for the army. I wanted to become stronger, to become her protector.
Jihasaha: Not long after that, the tribe was defeated, and the princess was taken as a hostage. And I had to just stand there and watch, no way to help her.
Jihasaha: Pathetic, huh? I always tell you you're useless, but really... I'm the useless one.
Jihasaha: Come on... you don't think it's funny?

Tingko: ...Actually, I know what you mean... 
I feel like I'm the same.
Tingko: Like you always say, there's nothing I can really do. Just stay by her side, keep her company.
Tingko: But I can never take away her pain. I can't really do anything to help.
Tingko: And this feeling, watching and being unable to do anything at all... It's unbearable.
Jihasaha: But you're always so... optimistic!
Tingko: Because if I show how I truly feel, it would just burden her even more. She doesn't want to see us sad.
Jihasaha: (I never knew she'd been keeping this all inside...)
Tingko: Alright, that's enough of this depressing stuff. Let's talk about how you're going to apologize to the princess. I have an idea...
Jihasaha: You... you'll help me out?
Tingko: Is that a problem?
Jihasaha: Shouldn't you hate me? Why would you help?
Tingko: Man, is your head filled with rocks or something? You want to help the princess, so I want to help you.
Jihasaha: ......
Tingko: That doesn't mean you're not still a huge pain in the butt~
Jihasaha: Hmph...
Jiyanama: Come quick! The princess has fainted!
